result.execSummary:
The defendant Waukon W Blackdeer was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Fredrickson.  Victim notification complied with. Defendant plead guilty to Count 2.  Count 1 dismissed but read in for sentencing purposes.   Court reviewed plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and element with the defendant.  Defendant understands.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis.  Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court finds that a factual basis exists, and the defendant is found guilty as plea to.  Joint recommendation for 1 year probation concurrent with his current probation.  Defendant did not exercise his right to allocution. Court ordered sentence withheld, 1 year probation, concurrent with his current probation.  Conditions: The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.   May apply for expungement if he successfully completes his current probation and this probation on this case. CC & domestic abuse surcharge.
Defendant appeared with counsel SPD Carly Sebion, appearing specially for Paul Fredrickson.  ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Set for plea/sent on 6-22-15 at 10:30.

REPORT FOR BOOKING.  Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.   As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.
Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived the time limits for holding the preliminary hearing.
